## The Story of Adam (30-39)

God announces to the angels that He is placing a **khalifa** (representative, steward) on the earth.

The angels push back:

> *"Will You place therein one who will cause corruption and shed blood, while we glorify You with praise and declare Your perfection?"* (30)

In other words: *why create humans? They'll just cause trouble. We're already here worshipping You perfectly.*

God doesn't explain. He simply says: *"I know what you do not know."*

Then He proves it. He teaches Adam the **names of all things** and asks the angels to identify them. They can't. Adam can. The point: humans were given a capacity for knowledge that even angels don't have. *That's* why they were created.

---

God commands the angels to **bow to Adam**. All of them do, *except Iblis* (Satan). He refuses out of arrogance.

Adam and his wife are placed in Paradise:

> *"O Adam, dwell, you and your wife, in Paradise and eat therefrom in ease and abundance from wherever you will. But do not approach this tree, lest you be among the wrongdoers."* (35)

Satan deceives them. They eat from it. They're expelled:

> *"Go down, all of you, as enemies to one another, and you will have upon the earth a place of settlement and provision for a time."* (36)

But here's something important: Adam **repents**, and God **accepts**:

> *"Then Adam received from his Lord some words, and He accepted his repentance. Indeed, it is He who is the Accepting of repentance, the Merciful."* (37)

In Islam, there's no concept of original sin passing to all of humanity. Adam made a mistake, asked for forgiveness, and was forgiven. Humanity starts with a clean slate.

