## Challenging the Prophets (75-123)

The remaining verses shift from ancient history to addressing the **Jewish communities of Medina** in Muhammad's time. The Quran essentially says: your ancestors did this, and *you're doing the same thing now*.

**Selective belief** (85-86): they accept parts of their scripture and reject other parts. The Quran asks: do you believe in some of the Book and disbelieve in the rest?

**Rejecting prophets** (87-91): whenever a messenger brought them something they didn't like, they either denied him or killed him. They rejected Jesus, and now they're rejecting Muhammad.

**The covenant** (83-84, 93): God took a covenant from them: worship none but God, be good to parents, relatives, orphans, and the poor, establish prayer, give charity. They turned away.

---

The section ends by establishing that guidance isn't exclusive to any one group:

> *"Say: We believe in God, and what was revealed to us, and what was revealed to Abraham, Ismail, Isaac, Jacob, and the tribes, and what was given to Moses and Jesus, and what was given to the prophets from their Lord. We make no distinction between any of them, and to Him we submit."* (136)

The message: this isn't about ethnic or religious labels. Abraham, Moses, Jesus, Muhammad: same God, same core message. Anyone who submits to God and does good has their reward.
